Sequenza pipeline

WU Fengyuan1

2021/8/30

Overview

Sequenza is a tool to analyze genomic sequencing data from paired normal-tumor samples, including cellularity and ploidy estimation; mutation and copy number (allele-specific and total copy number) detection, quantification and visualization.
There are two parts of sequenza, seperately run in python and R. Sequenza also requires samtools and tabix available in the environment.

Pipeline

1.Input files

Files Description
test_tumor.bam Tumor sample bam file generated by BWA and filtered by GATK toolkit
test_normal.bam Normal sample bam file generated by BWA and filtered by GATK toolkit.
reference.fasta Refernce genome, take care of version like hg38 or hg19

2.Produce a GC Wiggle track file

sequenzautils gc_wiggle \
  w 50 \
  --fasta reference.fasta \
  -o ref.gc50Base.wig.gz

3.Process BAM and Wiggle files to produce a seqz file

sequenzautils bam2seqz \
  -n normal.bam \
  -t tumor.bam \
  --fasta reference.fasta \
  -gc ref.gc50Base.wig.gz \
  -o out.seqz.gz

Optional: Parallelization

Run sequenza on multiple chromosomes at the same time, then merge the output files.
chr=(chr1 chr2 chr3 chr4 chr5 chr6 chr7 chr8 chr9 chr10 chr11 chr12 chr13 chr14 chr15 chr16 chr17 chr18 chr19 chr20 chr21 chr22 chrX chrY)

sequenza-utils bam2seqz \
  --fasta reference.fasta \
  -n tumor.bam \
  -t normal.bam \
  -gc ref.gc50Base.wig.gz \
  -o out.seqz.gz \
  --parallel 10 \
  --chromosome ${chr[*]}

seqz=`for chr in ${chr[*]};do printf "out_${chr}.seqz.gz ";done`
zcat $seqz|gawk '{if (NR!=1 && $1 != "chromosome") {print $0}}'|bgzip >out.seqz.gz

4.Post-process by binning the original seqz file

sequenzautils seqz_binning --seqz out.seqz.gz -w 50 -o out small.seqz.gz

5.Sequenza analysis (in R)

library(sequenza)

##sequenza.extract: process seqz data, normalization and segmentation
res=sequenza.extract("small.seqz.gz",verbose=FALSE,parallel=10)

##sequenza.fit: run grid-search approach to estimate cellularity and ploidy
cp=sequenza.fit(res)

##sequenza.results: write files and plots using suggested or selected solution
sequenza.results(sequenza.extract=res,cp.table=cp,sample.id=test,out.dir="result")

Results

1.seqz file

Column Description
chromosome Chromosome name
position Base position
base.ref Base in the reference genome
depth.normal Read depth in the normal sample
depth.tumor Read depth in the tumor sample
depth.ratio Ratio of depth.tumor and depth.normal
Af A-allele frequency in the tumor sample
Bf B-allele frequency in the tumor sample, in heterozygous positions only
zygosity.nomal Zygosity of the normal sample: hom for homozygous or het for heterozygous
GC.percent % GC content
good.reads Number of reads from the tumor sample which pass the quality threshold
AB.normal Base(s) found in the normal sample, sorted by allele frequency if more than one
AB.tumor Base(s) found in the tumor sample but not in the normal specimen, with their observed frequencies, separated by colons
tumor.strand Identical to AB.tumor but indicating, for each variant base, the fraction of reads oriented in the forward direction

2.gc_plots.pdf

Visualization of the GC correction in the normal and in the tumor sample.The color in the backgroud represents the number of N bases.

3.CP_contours.pdf

LPP:log posterior probability
Point estimate and its confidence region for ploidy and cellularity. The point estimate is the ploidy and cellularity with maximum LPP. The 95% confidence region (C.R.95%) is the smallest (not necessarily contiguous) set of points with a total posterior probability >0.95.

4.CP_contours.pdf

Copy number distribution of genomic regions.
Black circles and dots: Observed depth ratio and BAF values for each genomic segment. The background color is the representative joint LPP density calculated for the cellularity and ploidy estimates identified in CP_contours.pdf

5.chromosome_view.pdf

Chromosome plot indicating mutant allele frequency (top panel), B allele frequency (middle panel), and depth ratio (bottom panel).
Black dots in the middle and bottom panels are actually short bars, represent 1 Mb sequence. Blue bar indicates the interquartile range. Red lines indicate segmented values. The thin dotted lines indicate the expectation values under the fitted model.

6.genome_view.pdf

The copy number landscape of the whole genome.
The red and blue bars are a pair of sister chromosomes.Related data is stored in segments.txt.

7.segments.txt

Column Description
chromosome Chromosome
start.pos Start position of the segment
end.pos ENd position of the segment
Bf B-allele frequency value
N.BAF Number of observation to compute Bf in the segment
sd.BAF Standard deviation of Bf
depth.ratio Adjusted and normalized depth ratio tumor / normal
N.ratio Number of observation to compute depth.ratio in the segment
sd.ratio Standard deviation of depth.ratio
CNt Estimated total copy number value
A Estimated number of A-alleles
B Estimated number of B-alleles (minor allele)
LPP Log-posterior probability of the segment

8.Other files

File Description
alternative_solutions.txt List of all ploidy/cellularity alternative solution
CN_bars.pdf Bar plot representing the percentage of genome in the detected copy number states
confints_CP.txt Table of the confidence inerval of the best solution from the model
sequenza_cp_table.RData RData object dump of the maxima a posteriori computation
sequenza_extract.RData RData object dump of all the sample information
sequenza_log.txt Log with version and time information
